Here's the registration pattern:

```csharp
public static class MauiProgram
{
    public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
    {
        var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
        builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

        // HttpClient — single shared instance for connection pooling
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<HttpClient>();

        // Data service — singleton so every consumer shares one instance
        // and in-memory caches / auth tokens stay consistent
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<IDataService, DataService>();

        // ViewModels — transient so each navigation gets fresh state
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainViewModel>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailViewModel>();

        // Pages — transient so they pair 1:1 with their ViewModel
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainPage>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailPage>();

        return builder.Build();
    }
}
```

**Why each lifetime:**

| Registration | Lifetime | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `HttpClient` | **Singleton** | Reuses TCP connections; avoids socket exhaustion. (For production, prefer `IHttpClientFactory`.) |
| `IDataService` | **Singleton** | Shared state (caches, tokens, retry policies) should live once for the app's lifetime. |
| ViewModels | **Transient** | Each page navigation should get a clean ViewModel — no stale data from a previous visit. |
| Pages | **Transient** | Each navigation creates a fresh page bound to its own transient ViewModel. |

**When you'd use Scoped instead:** .NET MAUI doesn't have a built-in scope-per-navigation, so `AddScoped` behaves like singleton. Stick with transient + singleton unless you create custom scopes.

**Constructor injection then flows naturally:**

```csharp
public class DataService : IDataService
{
    private readonly HttpClient _http;
    public DataService(HttpClient http) => _http = http;
}

public class MainViewModel
{
    private readonly IDataService _data;
    public MainViewModel(IDataService data) => _data = data;
}

public partial class MainPage : ContentPage
{
    public MainPage(MainViewModel vm) => BindingContext = vm;
}
```

The DI container resolves the entire chain automatically when a page is requested via Shell routing or `IServiceProvider`.
